<br>
The problem with cowardice is really quite practical. If you are not willing to stand and fight, then usually someone else must take your place. <br>
<br>
At its root, cowardice is more than simple fear. It is an evasion of responsibility. Despite Cendan's inability to read my posts thoroughly, I hold British actions during the war in the highest regard.<br>
<br>
Why? Because they were more than willing to fight...all they asked was for the tools to do so. That is admirable.<br>
<br>
But certain of the other nations? We could have dropped rifles by the ton and they would not have used them. They were fine waiting for someone to come and liberate them...there was little resistance to be found, when we look at the actual population of these countries.<br>
<br>
I do not feel it is a cheap shot to call someone cowardly when they behave in a cowardly fashion. Nor do I feel it is a cheap shot to call someone irresponsible when they fail to live up to their responsibility. France wasn't exactly a nation of people in wheelchairs, were they?<br>
<br>
The bottomline is that some nations fought, even knowing that the consequences could be dire. Other nations offered little resistance, and thereby increased the difficulty for those who did.<br>
<br>
So contrary to what some people espouse in this thread, I will continue to remain old-fashioned in my views. Running away is cowardly, and should be called what it is. Standing your ground is brave, and should be admired accordingly.<br>
<br>
To excuse cowardice is to encourage it. And since MY country that has paid the majority of the bill twice in the last century, it is not in MY interest to excuse it.<br>
 <br>
<br>
When Continental Europe liberates America from a hostile Mexico and then rebuilds it from the ground up for FREE, then Europe can belittle my sorry ass. Because we'll deserve it. We will especially deserve it if we have large numbers of young men standing around doing nothing, waiting to be liberated.<br>
<br>
Will it be a cheap shot? Hell no. It'll be right on the money.<br>
